import matplotlib.pyplot as plt
import pandas as pd

def plot(data: pd.DataFrame):
    plt.style.use('ggplot')
    plt.figure(figsize=(12, 6))
    data = data.sort_values(by='population', ascending=False)
    plt.bar(data['state'], data['population'], color='blue')
    plt.xlabel('State')
    plt.ylabel('Population')
    plt.title('What is the distribution of population across the states?')
    plt.xticks(rotation=90)
    plt.tight_layout()
    return plt

data = pd.read_csv('population_engineers_hurricanes.csv')
chart = plot(data)
```

import matplotlib.pyplot as plt
import pandas as pd

def plot(data: pd.DataFrame):
    engineers_by_state = data.groupby('state')['engineers'].sum().sort_values(ascending=False)
    fig, ax = plt.subplots(figsize=(12, 6))
    ax.bar(engineers_by_state.index, engineers_by_state.values, color='blue')
    ax.set_xlabel('State')
    ax.set_ylabel('Number of Engineers')
    ax.set_title('What is the distribution of engineers across the states?')
    plt.xticks(rotation=90)
    plt.show()
    return plt

chart = plot(data)
```

import matplotlib.pyplot as plt
import pandas as pd

# Load data
data = pd.read_csv('population_engineers_hurricanes.csv')

# Group data by state and count the number of hurricanes
hurricanes_by_state = data.groupby('state')['hurricane'].count().reset_index()

# Sort the data by the number of hurricanes in descending order
hurricanes_by_state = hurricanes_by_state.sort_values(by='hurricane', ascending=False)

# Create a bar chart of hurricanes by state
fig, ax = plt.subplots(figsize=(10, 6))
ax.bar(hurricanes_by_state['state'], hurricanes_by_state['hurricane'], color='blue')

# Set chart title and axis labels
ax.set_title('What is the distribution of hurricanes across the states?')
ax.set_xlabel('State')
ax.set_ylabel('Number of Hurricanes')

# Rotate x-axis labels for better readability
plt.xticks(rotation=90)

# Show the chart
plt.show()
```
